---
/**
 * Audit-Trail Browser — public-facing chronological view of every
 * artefact the runtime has anchored.
 *
 * Three primitive entry kinds in v0:
 *
 *   - OTS Bitcoin anchor: a Bitcoin tx that anchored a Merkle
 *     commitment via OpenTimestamps; carries tx ids, block height,
 *     per-calendar branch verdicts.
 *   - WAT pin pack: a frozen artefact set with a SHA-256 manifest;
 *     pins prevent silent drift across runtime refactors.
 *   - Persona hash pin: a canonical-subset SHA-256 hash that pins a
 *     persona-definition shape (frontmatter-canonical in-hash, body
 *     out-of-hash); detects converter regressions.
 *
 * Sister page to `/verifier/`. The two pages cover different reading
 * modes:
 *
 *   - `/verifier/`     — how to read the output of a single
 *                        `wakir verify` run (one verdict, many receipts)
 *   - `/audit-trail/`  — the timeline of artefacts the runtime has
 *                        accumulated (many runs, many kinds, many
 *                        verdicts)
 *
 * Provisional content. The runtime does not yet emit a real audit-
 * trail JSON export; this page renders a build-time inlined sample
 * that points at real artefacts produced today (Sprint-2 deliveries
 * across `wirelang-eng`, `wat-eng`, `pengine`).
 *
 * Cross-Review-Hooks:
 *   - Comms Zone-G: micro-text review pending. Marketing-text below
 *     stays factual and follows the established pattern (no hype, no
 *     marketing-pill, no "trustless" badge).
 *   - WAT-Manifest-v2 schema sync with `wat-eng`: this page is a
 *     downstream consumer; any divergence between the rendered
 *     fields and the real audit-trail JSON output needs a paired
 *     edit on both sides.
 *   - Persona-hash-pin schema sync with `pengine`: same shape — a
 *     downstream consumer expectation, paired edit on divergence.
 */
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import AuditTrailEntry from "../components/AuditTrailEntry.astro";
import { sampleAuditTrail } from "../data/wakir-audit-trail-sample";

const title = "Wakir audit trail";
const description =
  "Chronological view of every artefact the runtime has anchored: OTS Bitcoin anchors, WAT pin packs, persona hash pins.";
---

<Base title={title} description={description}>
  <article class="essay">
    <header class="essay__header">
      <h1 class="essay__title">Wakir audit trail</h1>
      <p class="essay__lead">
        Every artefact the runtime produces gets anchored. The audit
        trail is the timeline of those anchors: Bitcoin transactions,
        pin packs, and persona hashes, in reverse-chronological order.
        This page renders a build-time inlined sample so a reviewer can
        see the shape before the runtime emits a real audit-trail
        export.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="essay__body">
      <p>
        For reading the output of a single verifier run, see
        <a href="/verifier/">how to read a Wakir verifier result</a>.
        The page you are reading now is the timeline view — many runs,
        many artefact kinds, many verdicts.
      </p>

      <h2>What the timeline contains</h2>

      <p>
        Three primitive entry kinds in this v0 surface:
      </p>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>OTS Bitcoin anchor.</strong> A Bitcoin transaction
          that anchored a Merkle commitment via OpenTimestamps. Carries
          tx ids, block height, and per-calendar branch verdicts. A
          fully finalised anchor has every calendar branch resolved to
          the same Bitcoin block. A partial anchor has at least one
          branch still aggregating. Block heights link to the public
          block explorer.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>WAT pin pack.</strong> A frozen artefact set with a
          SHA-256 manifest. Pins prevent silent drift across runtime
          refactors: a regression that changes the canonical shape of
          a pinned artefact produces an explicit pin break.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Persona hash pin.</strong> A canonical-subset
          SHA-256 hash that pins a persona-definition shape. The
          frontmatter is canonical and inside the hash; the body is
          outside. A persona-converter regression that drifts the
          canonical subset throws a determinism error against the pin.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>The current sample</h2>

      <p>
        The entries below point at real artefacts produced on
        Wakir-day 2026-05-07: the inter-agent NATS subject mapping
        spec, the manifest-v2 verifier stub, the persona-converter
        V9 pin, and Bitcoin anchors for the TV-2 and TV-3 audit-trail
        runs. The data is build-time inlined from
        <code>src/data/wakir-audit-trail-sample.ts</code>; the runtime
        export that will produce this shape directly is in flight.
      </p>

      <details class="wakir-audit-trail-filter">
        <summary>Filter by signature gate</summary>
        <div
          class="wakir-audit-trail-filter__controls"
          role="radiogroup"
          aria-label="Signature-gate filter"
        >
          <label>
            <input type="radio" name="signature-filter" value="all" checked />
            All entries
          </label>
          <label>
            <input type="radio" name="signature-filter" value="verified" />
            Verified only
          </label>
          <label>
            <input type="radio" name="signature-filter" value="unverified" />
            Unverified / rejected
          </label>
          <label>
            <input type="radio" name="signature-filter" value="mixed" />
            Mixed
          </label>
          <label>
            <input type="radio" name="signature-filter" value="none" />
            No signature row
          </label>
        </div>
        <p class="wakir-audit-trail-filter__note">
          The signature gate (Sprint-6 Tag-2) verifies manifest-level
          Ed25519 signatures against an opt-in public-key path. Filter
          surfaces only the signature outcome; the per-calendar branch
          verdicts on each OTS-anchor entry stay independent.
        </p>
      </details>

      <ol
        class="wakir-audit-trail-list"
        aria-label="Audit trail timeline"
        data-signature-filter="all"
      >
        {sampleAuditTrail.map((entry) => (
          <li class="wakir-audit-trail-list__item">
            <AuditTrailEntry entry={entry} />
          </li>
        ))}
      </ol>

      <script is:inline>
        // Progressive-enhancement filter. When JS is enabled, radio
        // changes flip the `data-signature-filter` attribute on the
        // list root; CSS `:has(...)` selectors handle the hide/show.
        // When JS is disabled the radio inputs are inert and the list
        // stays at `all` — every entry visible. No re-render needed;
        // the runtime check happens entirely in CSS.
        (function () {
          var list = document.querySelector(
            ".wakir-audit-trail-list[data-signature-filter]",
          );
          if (!list) return;
          var radios = document.querySelectorAll(
            'input[type="radio"][name="signature-filter"]',
          );
          for (var i = 0; i < radios.length; i++) {
            radios[i].addEventListener("change", function (event) {
              list.setAttribute(
                "data-signature-filter",
                event.target.value,
              );
            });
          }
        })();
      </script>

      <h2>Reading an OTS Bitcoin anchor entry</h2>

      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Pin hash.</strong> For an OTS anchor, the pin hash
          is the Bitcoin block hash that the OpenTimestamps commitment
          resolved to. Display-shortened in the entry header; the full
          hash is in the cell tooltip.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Block height.</strong> When every calendar branch
          agrees on a single height (the common case), the height
          links to the public block explorer. When branches diverge
          or are still pending, the per-branch table tells the full
          story.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Per-calendar branches.</strong> The same four public
          OpenTimestamps calendars used elsewhere in the runtime:
          <code>alice</code>, <code>bob</code>, <code>finney</code>,
          <code>catallaxy</code>. Verdict is <code>ok</code> for a
          finalised branch, <code>pending</code> for an aggregated-
          but-not-yet-anchored branch, <code>rejected</code> for a
          branch whose Merkle path or commit binding did not check
          out.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Reading a pin-pack entry</h2>

      <p>
        A pin pack lists the files that make up a frozen artefact set
        and the canonical-shape pin that the runtime expects against
        them. The entry shows the artefact filenames and line counts
        as a structural sketch — the load-bearing content is the pin
        hash itself, plus the test name that fails when the pin
        breaks.
      </p>

      <h2>Reading a signature-gate row</h2>

      <p>
        Entries delivered through the Sprint-6 Tag-2 driver-mode carry
        a manifest-signature gate outcome. The runtime verifier
        (<code>wat.verify.manifest_v2.verify_real_manifest_file</code>)
        emits one of six pinned values per hour-receipt: <code>verified</code>
        when the Ed25519 signature checks out against the supplied
        public key; <code>unsigned-permissive</code> when the manifest
        has no signature slot and the verifier was invoked in
        permissive mode; <code>unsigned-strict</code> when the verifier
        was invoked in strict mode against an unsigned manifest;
        <code>mismatch</code> when a well-formed signature did not
        verify; <code>structural-error</code> when the slot itself was
        malformed.
      </p>

      <p>
        A cohort with every value equal to <code>verified</code>
        renders the brand-accent pill and a summary like
        <code>verified (4 hours)</code>. Any divergence — even a single
        non-verified hour in an otherwise-verified cohort — switches the
        pill to a body-emphasis treatment and surfaces a per-hour
        breakdown table, so the reader cannot lose sight of a single
        failure inside an aggregate. The filter <code>&lt;details&gt;</code>
        above narrows the timeline to entries by signature outcome;
        with JavaScript disabled the page still works and shows
        everything.
      </p>

      <h2>Reading a persona-hash-pin entry</h2>

      <p>
        A persona-hash-pin entry shows the canonical-subset SHA-256
        and the named pin constants the runtime exports. A converter
        regression that drifts the canonical subset throws a
        determinism error that names the pin; the entry shows the test
        that catches that drift. The verify command reproduces the
        canonical-subset hash from a persona definition without
        running the runtime.
      </p>

      <h2>What is not here yet</h2>

      <p>
        This is a v0 timeline view. It currently supports a filter by
        signature-gate outcome (Sprint-6 Tag-2) but does not yet support
        filtering by entry kind, search by hash, or pagination beyond
        the build-time inlined sample. The runtime export that will
        feed a real audit-trail JSON is in flight; once it lands, this
        page will switch from a six-entry sample to the full timeline.
        Until then, the sample is real but partial.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Base>
